0.body: The Grime Progamming lauguage is designed to be like C with a modern syntax
0.title: About

1.body: Grime is a statically typed language that aims to bring a modern syntax to C whilst adding features such as strong and weak references to help prevent resource management errors.
1.title: Syntax

10.body:
Constructors can call methods however these methods can not mutate the class unless specified using the following syntax. class MyClass { var myField: Int; func myFunc(x: Int) -> Int { ret = myField + x; } mut func myMutFunc(x: Int) { myField = x; } build (x: Int) { myMutFunc(x); }
} Normal methods CAN NOT call mutable methods.

10.title: Extracting Methods From Constructors

11.title: Traits

12.body:
A class can only have one destructor. This destructor is defined with the following syntax and is only ever called by the runtime not the programmer. It allows the programmer to do things like close files or clean up any unsafe memory that was being used when the object is garbage collected. class MyClass : MyTrait { demolish { }
}
12.title: Destructor

14.title: Functions

3.body:
In Grime the entry point of a program is the main function. mod test::entry use func std::io::println func main() -> Int { println("Hello, World");
}
3.title: The Entry Point

4.body:
mod test::includes use mod std::maths // includes the math module
use trait std::string::String // includes String trait
use func std::io::println // includes the println function from std::io func main() -> Int { val vec1 : [Float] = {1.0f, 6.0f, 3.0f} val vec2 : [Float] = {3.0f, 4.0f, 2.0f} val vec3 : [Float] = maths::dot3f(vec1, vec2) del vec1 del vec2 val out : [UByte] = String.formatCreate("({0}, {1}, {2})", vec3) // no string:: needed as trait included not mod del vec3 println(out) // no io:: needed because func included not mod del out ret = 0
}
4.title: Includes

6.body:
A class is defined with the following syntax class MyClass { } class MyClass { var MyField: Int;
}
6.title: Adding Fields

7.title: Adding Methods

8.body:
Constructors are similar to methods except they can mutate the fields of an object. However, constructors delete all previous contents of an object. Constructors can be named or unnamed but there can only be one unnamed constructor per class. class MyClass { val myField: Int; build (val field: Int) { myField = field; }
}
8.title: Adding a Constructor

9.body:
class MyClass { var myField: Int; build create(val field: Int) { myField = field; }
}
